sentences: Željko Joksimović (Serbian Cyrillic: Жељко Јоксимовић, pronounced [ʒěːʎko jǒksimoʋitɕ] (listen); born 20 April 1972) is a Serbian vocalist, composer, songwriter, multi-instrumentalist and producer.
He represented Serbia and Montenegro in the Eurovision Song Contest 2004 with the song "Lane moje", placing second.
He also represented Serbia in the Eurovision Song Contest 2012 with the song "Nije ljubav stvar", placing third.
Željko Joksimović was born on 20 April 1972 in Belgrade and grew up in the city of Valjevo.
He graduated music at the University of Belgrade and launched his professional music career in 1997.
In 1998 he won a contest at the Pjesma Mediterana festival with the song "Pesma Sirena", which led to opportunities to perform at more prestigious festivals in Belarus.
In 1999 he won his first big prize when becoming the Grand Prix winner of the International Festival of Arts Slavianski Bazaar in Vitebsk, Belarus.
In 2001, Joksimović released his second studio album Vreteno named after a song on the album.
111 was released in 2002, soaring to No.1 on the pop charts of Serbia and other countries of the region.
In 2003, Joksimović wrote the song "Čija si" for Macedonian music singer Toše Proeski which led him to win Beovizija.
Eurovision Song Contest 2004 =

Serbia and Montenegro, sending an entrant for the first time to 2004 Eurovision Song Contest, decided on their representative through Evropesma 2004, a music festival and contest in Serbia and Montenegro.

sentences: === 2008–2011: Eurovision hosting and Ljubavi =
In early 2008, Željko Joksimović composed a song that was performed by Jelena Tomašević in the Serbian national final for the Eurovision song selection, Beovizija 2008, called "Oro".
In early 2008, Željko Joksimović composed a song that was performed by Jelena Tomašević in the Serbian national final for the Eurovision song selection, Beovizija 2008, called "Oro".
Because the Eurovision Song Contest 2007 has been won by Serbia, the contest that year came in the country.

On 24 March 2008 it was announced by the 2008 Eurovision organisers RTS that together with Jovana Janković he would host the Eurovision Song Contest 2008 in Belgrade, giving him two roles in the contest.

On 24 March 2008 it was announced by the 2008 Eurovision organisers RTS that together with Jovana Janković he would host the Eurovision Song Contest 2008 in Belgrade, giving him two roles in the contest.
After a year of a music pause he released his fifth studio album named Ljubavi (2009) by the production of Minacord and City Records.
In early 2010 he released the second single from the album called "Žena Za Sva Vremena".
On 12 June 2010, he performed his biggest concert yet.
Joksimović represented Serbia in the Eurovision Song Contest 2012 in Baku, Azerbaijan.
He married Jovana Janković in January 2012.
Eurovision Song Contest 2015
Željko Joksimović was invited by RTCG to compose song for Knez who represented Montenegro in the Eurovision Song Contest 2015 in Vienna, Austria.
In November 2018, Željko Joksimović had a concert in Arena Zenica – after eight-year break.
On 9 August, Joksimović closed Zenica summer fest 2019 by free public two-hour performance on Zenica city square.
